her=Infodisc.fr |accessdate=March 31, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929225042/http://www.infodisc.fr/S_Certif_Or.php?debut=400 |archivedate=September 29, 2013 }}</ref>|accessdate=September 28, 2011}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|type=single|title=No Scrubs|artist=TLC|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=2019|accessdate=May 7, 2019|refname=\"fimi\"}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=New Zealand|artist=TLC|title=No Scrubs|relyear=1999|certyear=1999|type=single|award=Platinum|id=1023|recent=website|accessdate=November 21, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Sweden|artist=TLC|title=No Scrubs|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=1999|type=single|accessdate=November 21, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|artist=TLC|title=No Scrubs|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1999|certyear=2018|salesamount=677,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/tlcs-official-top-10-biggest-selling-singles-revealed__18982/|title=TLC's Top 10 biggest selling singles revealed|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=May 9, 2017|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=TLC|title=No Scrubs|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=1999}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|FrLequ6dUdM|\"No Scrubs\" Music video}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|tlc|no-scrubs}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{TLC songs}}\n\n[[Category:1999 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one dance singles in Canada]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kandi Burruss]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lisa Lopes]]\n[[Category:1998 songs]]\n[[Category:LaFace Records singles]]\n[[Category:Arista Records singles]]\n[[Category:TLC (group) songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Hype Williams]]\n[[Category:Songs with feminist themes]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kevin \"She'kspere\" Briggs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tameka Cottle]]\n[[Category:Dance-pop songs]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|1999 single by TLC}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = No Scrubs\n| cover      = Tlc-noscubs2.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[TLC (group)|TLC]]\n| album      = [[FanMail]]\n| B-side     = [[Silly Ho]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1999|02|02}}\n| format     = \n*[[CD single]]\n*[[cassette single|cassette]]\n*[[7-inch single|7\"]]\n*[[12-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   = December 1998\n| studio     = D.A.R.P. <small>(Atlanta, Georgia)</small>\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] <!-- This genre is sourced in the \"critical reception\" section. Please DO NOT ADD other genres without citing one or more reliable sources that explicitly describe the song as such. -->\n| length     = \n*3:34 (album version)\n*{{Duration|4:00}} (main mix with Left Eye)\n| label      = \n*[[LaFace Records|LaFace]]\n*[[Arista Records|Arista]]\n| writer     = \n*[[Kevin \"She'kspere\" Briggs]]\n*[[Kandi Burruss]]\n*[[Tameka Cottle|Tameka \"Tiny\" Cottle]]\n*[[Lisa Lopes]]\n| producer   = She'kspere\n| prev_title = [[Diggin' on You]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[Unpretty]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc = {{External music video|{{YouTube|FrLequ6dUdM|\"No Scrubs\"}}\n }}{{Audio sample|type=single|file=No Scrubs.ogg}}\n}}\n\n\"'''No Scrubs'''\" is a song recorded by American [[girl group]] [[TLC (group)|TLC]] for their third studio album ''[[FanMail]]'' (1999). The lyrics posit that a man who does not have his own car is a \"scrub\" (also known as a \"buster\") and is undesirable as a romantic or sexual partner. [[LaFace Records]] and [[Arista Records]] released it as the album's [[lead single]] on February 2, 1999. The song was written by [[Kevin \"She'kspere\" Briggs]] alongside former [[Xscape (group)|Xscape]] members, [[Kandi Burruss]] and [[Tameka Cottle|Tameka \"Tiny\" Cottle]]. The [[single version]] containing self-written rap by [[Lisa Lopes|Lisa \"Left Eye\" Lopes]] was not included on the album ''FanMail'', and later appeared in a slightly shorter edit on ''[[Now and Forever: The Hits]]'' and ''[[20 (TLC album)|20]]''. \"No Scrubs\" was the first time [[Rozonda Thomas|Rozonda \"Chilli\" Thomas]] took the sole [[lead vocals]] on any TLC single. The album version of the song won [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group]] and [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]] at [[42nd Annual Grammy Awards]].\n\n\"No Scrubs\" met with international success. It became TLC's third number-one single and eighth top 10 single on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It also earned them their second Grammy Award nomination for [[Record of the Year]]. \"No Scrubs\" is one of TLC's [[signature song]]s and was the second-biggest Hot 100 single of 1999 in the U.S., only behind [[Cher]]'s \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\", according to ''Billboard''{{'}}s year-end charts. On the decade end chart for 1990\u201399, \"No Scrubs\" was ranked at number 33. The single was certified Platinum in the UK and Platinum in New Zealand.\n\n==Background==\nThe song was initially written by [[Kandi Burruss]] on an old envelope while sitting in her car, in which she \"freestyled the entire song while just driving down a highway: the verse, hook, pre-chorus, the whole thing.\"<ref name=\"FanMail20\"/> The song was initially meant for Burruss and [[Tameka Cottle]] to record together, however [[Dallas Austin]] decided to give the song to [[TLC (group)|TLC]] as their first single for ''[[FanMail]]'', with [[Rozonda Thomas|Chilli]] singing the lead vocals.<ref name=\"FanMail20\"/> Austin further emphasized that the song was a breakthrough for Chilli, as he felt that \"It was a great way to expose her; being a secondary vocalist was not just her purpose.\"<ref name=\"FanMail20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8499567/tlc-fanmail-interview-20th-anniversary-dallas-austin|title=TLC's 'FanMail' Turns 20: A Track-By-Track Retrospective With the Girl Group and Behind-the-Scenes Collaborators|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Gracie|first=Bianca|date=February 22, 2019|access-date=October 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223013401/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8499567/tlc-fanmail-interview-20th-anniversary-dallas-austin|archive-date=February 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"No Scrubs\" is described by ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' as \"a scathing critique on men at the bottom of the dating pool\".<ref name=\"VibeFanMail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2019/02/tlc-fanmail-anniversary-digital-era-intimacy|title=20 Years Of TLC's 'FanMail': A Futurist Prelude To Digital Era Intimacy|last=Whaley|first=Nateleg\u00e9|website=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=February 23, 2019|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 2014, Cottle described the process of creating the song with Burruss:<ref name=\"RollingStone2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/tameka-tiny-harris-on-michael-jacksons-xscape-connection-244108/|title=Tameka 'Tiny' Harris on Michael Jackson's Xscape Connection|last=Murray|first=Nick|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=May 1, 2014|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref><blockquote>I wanna talk about a screw-up, a guy that's a screw-up that doesn't have their own business in order. It came from a previous relationship that she was in. And we took that and wrote about what we call a scrub.</blockquote> The song contains \"airy remnants of an electronic guitar\", which begins with Chilli's angelic vocals.<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2019/02/tlc-no-scrubs-anniversary|title=TLC's \"No Scrubs\" Is Still On Top 20 Years Later|last=Thompson|first=Wanna|website=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=February 2, 2019|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> The word \"scrub\" originated from [[Atlanta]], which was initially used as a slang term for a person who couldn't get their life together.<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\"/> The composition of \"No Scrubs\" is based on [[Time signature|{{Time signature|4|4}} common time]], the tempo is 93 [[Tempo|BPM]] and is played in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[A-flat major]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tunebat.com/Info/No-Scrubs-TLC/1KGi9sZVMeszgZOWivFpxs|title=Key & BPM for No Scrubs by TLC|publisher=Tunebat|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> According to the [[sheet music]] published at Musicnotes.com by [[EMI Music Publishing]], the vocal range of TLC spans from the low note F#<sub>3</sub> to the high note of C#<sub>5</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0026394|title=No Scrubs|website=Musicnotes.com|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nIn 1999, \"No Scrubs\" was listed on ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s annual poll [[Pazz & Jop]] at number one.<ref>{{cite web|title=1999|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2005/10/18/1999/|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=October 18, 2005}}</ref> The song also came in at number two in the ''[[NME]]'' Top Tracks of 1999 and number 45 in the ''NME'' 100 Best Songs of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=1999|url=http://www.nme.com/bestalbumsandtracksoftheyear/1999-2-1045360|website=[[NME]]|accessdate=January 30, 2018|date=October 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=100 Best Songs of the 1990s|url=http://www.nme.com/list/100-best-songs-of-the-1990s-1157|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=NME|date=May 8, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked the song at number 10 in their list of the 50 Best Songs of the Nineties.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheffield|first1=Rob|author-link=Rob Sheffield|title=50 Best Songs of the Nineties|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-songs-of-the-nineties-w432840/tlc-no-scrubs-1999-w432870|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 8, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, [[VH1]] listed the song at number 22 in their list of the 40 Greatest [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] Songs of the 90s, ranking behind TLC's 1995 international single \"[[Waterfalls (TLC song)|Waterfalls]]\" which placed at number 6.<ref>{{cite news|title=40 Greatest R&B Songs of the '90s (Complete List)|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/1720/40-greatest-rb-songs-of-the-90s/|accessdate=January 30, 2018|publisher=[[VH1]]|date=June 28, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' named the song #42 on their list of 100 Greatest Girl Group Songs of All Time.<ref>{{cite news|title=100 Greatest Girl Group Songs of All Time: Critics' Picks|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7857816/100-greatest-girl-group-songs|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"No Scrubs\" jumped to number one upon the single's release on the April 3, 1999 issue of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Faison|first1=Datu|title=Datu Faison's rhythm section|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 3, 1999|volume=111|issue=14|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SQ0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40|accessdate=January 30, 2018|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> The single stayed at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for four weeks from April 10, 1999, to May 7, 1999.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bronson|first1=Fred|author-link=Fred Bronson|title=Distaff Destiny: Leaders of the Pack|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 17, 1999|volume=111|issue=29|page=118|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kAgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA118|access-date=January 30, 2018|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> The single stayed in the top-ten of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 for 17 consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\"/> \"No Scrubs\" airplay was at the time, the first song to peak with over 140 million audience impressions, and was crowned the Top Airplay Song of 1999.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pietroluongo|first1=Silvio|last2=Patel|first2=Minal|last3=Jessen|first3=Wade|title=Singles Minded|journal=Billboard|date=January 19, 2002|volume=114|issue=3|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Q8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA77|access-date=January 30, 2018|issn=0006-2510|quote=The record now reverts to Arista, which was the first label to surpass the 140 million audience mark in May 1999 with TLC's 'No Scrubs.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pietroluongo|first1=Silvio|last2=Patel|first2=Minal|last3=Jessen|first3=Wade|title=Singles Minded|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 12, 2002|volume=114|issue=2|page=83|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Q8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA83|access-date=January 30, 2018|issn=0006-2510|quote=In two prior years, only TLC's 'No Scrubs' in 1999 topped the 140-million listener mark, but three had such weeks in 2001's chart year, including 'Independent Women.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bronson|first1=Fred|title=The year in charts|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 25, 1999<!-- \u2013January 1, 2000 -->|volume=111|issue=52|page=YE-12|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=SL680-PA12|access-date=January 30, 2018|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> It holds the record for most weeks at number one on the [[Rhythmic Top 40]] with 15 weeks,<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\"/> as well as being ranked at number two on [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1999|''Billboard'''s Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1999]], only behind [[Cher]]'s \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\".<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\"/>\n\nIn Australia, \"No Scrubs\" was a huge success, spending seven consecutive weeks at the summit of the [[ARIA Charts]] from May 2, 1999 to June 20, 1999.<ref name=\"aus\"/> In the United Kingdom, it peaked at number three on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming TLC's highest-charting single in Britain.<ref>{{cite news|last=Myers|first=Justin|title=Official Charts Flashback 1999: TLC \u2013 No Scrubs|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-flashback-1999-tlc-no-scrubs__4745/|access-date=January 30, 2018|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=March 28, 2014}}</ref> The song was certified platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/|title=BRIT Certified|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|access-date=August 16, 2018|format=enter \"No Scrubs\" into the \"Keywords\" box, then select \"Search\"}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\nThe [[Hype Williams]]-directed video was set in a futuristic space station, where the trio wore silver and blue metallic outfits.<ref name=\"VibeFanMail\"/> It includes a dance sequence where the women dance in front of the \"TLC\" logo. The Main Mix is used in the video in place of the album version, which includes a rap verse by [[Lisa Lopes|Left Eye]]. [[Tionne Watkins|T-Boz]] described how the group went all out during production of the video, with her being specifically excited about \"wearing the all-white outfit\", while [[Rozonda Thomas|Chilli]] initially felt apprehensive about going on the swing, constantly practicing before the shoot until she did not want to get off afterwards.<ref name=\"FanMail20\"/> The scene at the end of the video showing the three fighting each other and being silly was a result of the tube moving and the group attempting to fight against the moving set, with Chilli and Left Eye hitting each other by accident.<ref name=\"FanMail20\"/> American [[drag queen]] [[RuPaul]] also appeared off-camera to see them.<ref name=\"FanMail20\"/> The video is stylistically similar to [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Janet Jackson]]'s music video, \"[[Scream/Childhood|Scream]]\", as well as the [[Busta Rhymes]] and Janet Jackson music video, \"[[What's It Gonna Be?!]]\", which was also directed by Williams.<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\"/>\n\n===Synopsis===\nThe video features the women in three different colored space-suits: white, black, silver, and Left Eye in blue. When there are shots of the women together they have two different outfits: black and silver. T-Boz's hair is fuchsia in the video. It also features a scene of Chilli on a swing singing, alongside T-Boz dancing as well as Left Eye. As Left Eye's rap begins, she is positioned in a garage wearing white clothes while rapping, and practicing martial arts in a futuristic blue outfit in a separate scene.<ref name=\"VibeFanMail\"/> She is filmed by a drone, as she continues rapping; \"Can't forget the focus on the picture in front of me/You as clear as DVD on digital TV screens.\"<ref name=\"VibeFanMail\"/> The final scene shows TLC fighting each other, while also dancing and having fun.\n\n===Reception===\nThe futuristic music video received massive airplay on [[MTV]] and [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]].{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} It also won the group the [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Group Video]] at the [[1999 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1999/mtvvmas.htm|title=1999 MTV Video Music Awards|website=Rock on the Net|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> As of March 2020, the video has over 200 million views on [[YouTube]].\n\n==Legacy==\n===Covers===\nUK band [[The Saturdays]] covered the track on [[BBC Radio 1]]'s [[Live Lounge]] segment in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saturdays Live Lounge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03cndnx |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> Philadelphia singer/songwriter [[Avi Wisnia]] covered the song on his 2010 album ''Something New''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviwisnia.com/music/ |title=Music \u00ab Avi Wisnia |publisher=Aviwisnia.com |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Grites |first1=Rebecca |title=Band of the Week: Avi Wisnia |url=https://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/attheshore/nightlife/band-of-the-week-avi-wisnia/article_42935a12-5422-54a9-9202-2b82284d33cb.html |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |work=[[The Press of Atlantic City]] |date=March 25, 2010}}</ref> [[Karmin (band)|Karmin]] covered \"No Scrubs\" in 2011 shortly before releasing \"Crash Your Party\", connecting the \"throwback cover\" of the song to the [[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)|\"old school sample\"]] in \"[[Crash Your Party]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Karmin Covers TLC's 'No Scrubs' [Video] |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/10/10/karmin-covers-tlcs-no-scrubs-video/ |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |work=Rap-Up |date=October 10, 2011}}</ref> [[Kelly Clarkson]] covered the song during her 2012 Summer Tour on August 23, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rubenstein|first1=Jenna Hally|title=Kelly Clarkson Covers TLC's 'No Scrubs,'; The Game Is Forever Changed (VIDEO)|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2301962/kelly-clarkson-tlc-no-scrubs-cover-video/|access-date=July 2, 2018|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=August 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe cast of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' covered the song in the \"[[Sadie Hawkins (Glee)|Sadie Hawkins]]\" episode of [[Glee (season 4)|the show's fourth season]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Slezak|first1=Michael|title=Glee Recap: Hawkins-Like Vision [Updated]|url=https://tvline.com/2013/01/24/glee-recap-season-4-sadie-hawkins/|access-date=July 2, 2018|website=TVLine|date=January 25, 2013}}</ref> It was performed by [[Kevin McHale (actor)|Kevin McHale]], [[Chord Overstreet]], [[Blake Jenner]], [[Samuel Larsen]] and [[Darren Criss]]. [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]] covered the song alongside [[The xx]]'s \"[[Angels (The xx song)|Angels]]\" in a mash-up entitled \"No Angels\", which features on their 2012 mixtape ''Other People's Heartache, Pt. 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fadedglamour.co.uk/2012/12/download-bastille-other-peoples-heartache-2.html|title=Download: Bastille - Other People's Heartbreak, Pt. 2|publisher=Faded Glamour|date=December 11, 2012|access-date=January 6, 2013}}</ref> Scout Niblett covered the song on the album ''It's Up to Emma''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fennessy|first1=Kathy|title=Scout Niblett: No Wigs, No Scrubs|url=https://www.thestranger.com/lineout/archives/2013/05/07/scout-niblett-no-wigs-no-scrubs|access-date=July 2, 2018|website=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]|date=May 7, 2013}}</ref> [[Kacey Musgraves]] covered the song during her tour \"Same Tour, Different Trailer\" in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Keller|first1=Jordan|title=Kacey Musgraves\u2019 2015 Cover Of \"No Scrubs\" May Be The Best Cover Of All Time|url=https://www.onecountry.com/country-artists/kacey-musgraves/kacey-musgraves-no-scrubs-2015/|access-date=July 2, 2018|work=One Country|date=January 29, 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, [[Weezer]] released a cover of the song, which was included on their twelfth studio album, ''[[Weezer (Teal Album)|Teal Album]]''.<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\"/>\n<!--Please add notable covers contained with reliable sources-->\n\n===Samples in other songs===\nIn 2013, DJ and producer [[Le Youth]] sampled the song in his single \"[[Dance with Me (Le Youth song)|Dance with Me]]\", which reached number 11 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corner|first1=Lewis|title=Le Youth premieres 'Dance With Me' music video - watch|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/new-music/news/a543511/le-youth-premieres-dance-with-me-music-video-watch/|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=January 13, 2014}}</ref> [[XXYYXX]] sampled the song in his \"Good Enough\" track on the album ''XXYYXX''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stieb |first1=Matt |title=XXYYXX Isn't Just Good for His Age \u2014 He's Just Good |url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/music/xxyyxx-isnt-just-good-for-his-age-hes-just-good-8276746 |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |work=[[Miami New Times]] |date=February 25, 2016}}</ref> While not incidentally crediting the writers, the writers on \"No Scrubs\" were later credited on [[Ed Sheeran]]'s \"[[Shape of You]]\" as it interpolates \"No Scrubs\".<ref>{{cite web|title=ACE Repertory|url=https://www.ascap.com/ace#ace/search/workID/891742252 |website=ASCAP|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> \"[[SOS (Avicii song)|SOS]]\" by [[Avicii]] featuring [[Aloe Blacc]] contains an [[Interpolation (popular music)|interpolation]] of the song, as the songwriters were credited.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/107045332/track/107045333|title=SOS / Avicii|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other responses===\nAfter TLC released \"No Scrubs\" in 1999, [[Sporty Thievz]] made an [[answer song]] called \"[[No Pigeons]]\" that same year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Century|first1=Douglas|title=A Hip-Hop Battle of the Sexes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/09/style/noticed-a-hip-hop-battle-of-the-sexes.html|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 9, 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Partridge|first1=Kenneth|title=TLC's Rozonda 'Chilli' Thomas Reflects on the 15th Anniversary of 'No Scrubs'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6049079/tlcs-rozonda-chilli-thomas-reflects-on-the-15th-anniversary-of-no|accessdate=January 30, 2018|work=Billboard|date=April 10, 2014}}</ref> [[Rozonda Thomas|Chilli]] felt that they made the song because they felt threatened by the song's success, stating that \"they can't take the heat!\"<ref name=\"FanMail20\"/> The word \"scrub\" rapidly spread globally, with the vocabulary being commonly used by women.<ref name=\"VibeNoScrubs\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''US CD single'''\n# \"No Scrubs\" (album version) (dirty) \u2013 3:39\n# \"No Scrubs\" (instrumental) \u2013 3:37\n\n'''European CD single'''\n# \"No Scrubs\" (album version) (clean) \u2013 3:37\n# \"No Scrubs\" (main mix w/ [[Left Eye]]) (clean) \u2013 4:00\n# \"No Scrubs\" (instrumental) \u2013 3:37\n# \"[[Silly Ho]]\" (album version) (dirty) \u2013 4:16\n\n'''UK CD 1'''\n# \"No Scrubs\" (album version) (clean) \u2013 3:37\n# \"No Scrubs\" (main mix w/ Left Eye) (clean) \u2013 4:00\n# \"Silly Ho\" (album version) (dirty) \u2013 4:16\n{{col-2}}\n'''UK CD 2'''\n# \"No Scrubs\" (album version) (clean) \u2013 3:39\n# \"[[Waterfalls (TLC song)|Waterfalls]]\" (radio version) \u2013 4:19\n# \"[[Creep (TLC song)|Creep]]\" (radio version) \u2013 4:26\n\n'''French CD single'''\n# \"No Scrubs\" (album version) (clean) \u2013 3:39\n# \"[[Waterfalls (TLC song)|Waterfalls]]\" \u2013 4:36\n\n'''US vinyl single'''\n# \"No Scrubs\" (main mix w/ Left Eye) (clean) \u2013 4:00\n# \"No Scrubs\" (main mix w/ Left Eye) (dirty) \u2013 4:00\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1999)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|1|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true|refname=\"aus\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|26|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|5|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|3|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|1|chartid=8125|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadaadultcontemporary|27|chartid=8166|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadadance|1|chartid=7455|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Denmark ([[IFPI]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jAgEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA61&dq=tlc%20no%20scrubs%20denmark&pg=PA61#v=onepage&q=tlc%20no%20scrubs%20denmark&f=false|title=Hits Of The World|work=Billboard|page=61|date=July 3, 1999|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1999/MM-1999-06-19.pdf|title=Euro Chart Hot 100|work=Music & Media|page=13|date=June 19, 1999|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|2\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|5|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|4|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|songid=3879|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Greece ([[IFPI Greece|IFPI]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1999/MM-1999-07-17.pdf|title=Top National Sellers|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=16|issue=29|page=11|date=July 17, 1999|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Iceland ([[\u00cdslenski listinn|\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://timarit.is/files/12779924.pdf#navpanes=1&view=FitH|title=\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40 (NR. 319 Vikuna 16.4. \u2013 23.4. 1999)|publisher=Dagbla\u00f0i\u00f0 V\u00edsir|accessdate=July 14, 2018|language=is}}</ref>\n|11\t\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 24, 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italy (''[[Musica e dischi]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1999/MM-1999-07-17.pdf|title=Top National Sellers|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=16|issue=29|page=11|date=July 17, 1999|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|7\n|-\n!scope=\u201crow\u201d|Japan (Tokio Hot 100)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.j-wave.co.jp/original/tokiohot100/cgi-bin/top100.cgi|title=Tokio Hot 100| date=March 7, 1999|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|3|year=1999|week=21|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 24, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|3|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|1|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|7|artist=TLC|song=No Scrubs|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|11|date=19990515|rowheader